Moral economics is the application of economics principles to altruistic endeavors.

Moral economics includes incentive mechanisms and coordination mechanisms.

Incentive mechanisms include [certificates of impact](https://rationalaltruist.com/2014/11/15/certificates-of-impact/) and [ompact prizes](https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/2cCDhxmG36m3ybYbq/impact-prizes-as-an-alternative-to-certificates-of-impact).

Coordination mechanisms include [moral trades](http://www.amirrorclear.net/files/moral-trade.pdf) and [donation swaps](https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/YiFdK2D8xq2YxyhNi/can-we-set-up-a-system-for-international-donation-trading).

